    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it's still super frustrating. so basically most of my money is just disappearing into interest instead of actually paying off what i owe. is there like a specific mathematical way they calculate that monthly charge? like is it just a flat percentage or something else?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Instead of a flat percentage, the interest is calculated using the amortization formula, which applies your annual interest rate to the remaining principal balance ($\\text{Principal Balance} \\times \\frac{\\text{Annual Interest Rate}}{12}$). This calculation ensures that each month's interest charge is dynamically determined by whatever balance you have left. As your principal balance decreases, the amount of interest charged each month also naturally decreases.",
      "source": "target",
